{
  "answer": "**The work is the *Gaṇapatitattva* (author unknown), Chapter 1.**[^1]\n\nThis chapter closes with the specified *paṅlukatan* (purification ritual) for Gaṇapati, a son of Śiva, depicted in a *rajah* (magical drawing) on ivory bamboo (*ampel gading*) with a discus in his left hand and a mace in his right hand.[^2] The ritual uses exactly these materials: a white-and-yellow *ajuman* set; a *sucī* offering with a white crested chicken as its main dish; water in a copper vessel (*sanku*); *sudhāmala* flowers with *pras* and *santun* offerings; a monetary offering of 1100; and *samsam* of *katima* leaves.[^2] The rite's protections are effective against an epidemic, epilepsy, spirit affliction, and destruction caused by animals.[^3]\n\nThe requested invocation is:  \n> Destroyer of all poisons, Lord of Kāladṛṅga and Dṛṅgī (?),  \n> who makes opposing diseases faint, who gives life to the three worlds.[^4]\n\n[^1]: *Gaṇapatitattva*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136/01/translation/).\n[^2]: *Gaṇapatitattva*, [Chapter 1, p-36c962](/works/unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136/01/translation/#p-36c962).\n[^3]: *Gaṇapatitattva*, [Chapter 1, p-0dbd7d](/works/unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136/01/translation/#p-0dbd7d).\n[^4]: *Gaṇapatitattva*, [Chapter 1, p-a89bcc](/works/unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136/01/translation/#p-a89bcc).",
